text.tspan: Find places to park on BW's campus. App can help students and faculty
quickly and safely find available parking. (ParkBW isn't necessarily the
- Needs to be fast and intuitive to encourage use.
- Should work on both mobile and desktop.
- Should we try to minimize taps to use?
- What can we do to avoid making our web app feeling clunky?
- Do we use too much yellow? Should it be replaced with a neutral color?
Most users will probably use ParkBW from their phone, so we need to make
sure it works well on mobile.
- On mobile, buttons can have more padding than on Desktop.
- Bottom Navigation allows for easy usability in one hand.
- Park: Select a lot and park
- My Spot: Show lot where parked
- More: Show menu for settings, about, etc
- Lot image hidden on home screen to save space.
- Android and iOS both handle a "back" action.
- In Chrome/Safari, users can use browser UI or gesture.
- As a PWA, users can use their system's back gesture or button.
It's possible a student wants to access the site from a PC if they didn't have time to do so
on their phone. The website should adapt for these users.
- We can move navigation to the top since reachability isn't an issue.
- We can put navigation buttons in the top bar thanks to wider canvas.
- Buttons can be slimmed down since the user is now using a mouse
- The lot is shown on home screen with the assumption the screen is larger.
- Should we limit how far to the left and right buttons can go, for users of very wide displays?
